By DUNCAN MANSFIELD<br>
Associated Press Writer<br>
<br>
About 200 peace activists danced in the street leading to the Y-12 nuclear <br>
weapons plant Sunday, blocking access until scores of law enforcement <br>
officers arrived and arrested six protesters.<br>
<br>
The six women - including one from North Carolina - led the demonstrators to <br>
the plant gate and demanded entry as civilian weapons inspectors. They were <br>
arrested without resistance by Oak Ridge police on a misdemeanor charge of <br>
blocking a roadway.<br>
<br>
&quot;We have a strong conviction that what is happening here at Y-12 is a threat <br>
to human life and under certain conditions to the planet itself,&quot; said Judy <br>
Ross, 80, of Balsam, N.C., just before her arrest.<br>
<br>
Meagan Carter, another of those taken into custody, offered encouragement to <br>
the crowd earlier as they gathered under tents in freezing temperatures and <br>
occasional snow flurries.<br>
<br>
&quot;Remaining silent on this life and death issue will only convince the Bush <br>
administration that you agree with their aggressive nuclear posture,&quot; said <br>
Carter, a 31-year-old graduate student in religious studies at the <br>
University of Tennessee in Knoxville.<br>
<br>
Across a barricade at the plant entrance, the protesters hung a banner: <br>
&quot;Y-12 nuclear weapons plant, closed for life.&quot; The sign remained in place <br>
about an hour.<br>
<br>
About 40 counterdemonstrators held their own rally. They waved American <br>
flags and played patriotic songs on a boombox as the peace activists marched <br>
past.<br>
<br>
&quot;Support the troops,&quot; a counterprotester with a flag called out.<br>
<br>
&quot;Support the people, not the corporations,&quot; a peace demonstrator shouted <br>
back.<br>
<br>
Watching the anti-war protesters, Mike Jacobs, a 55-year-old Army veteran <br>
who served in Vietnam, shook his head. &quot;This just can't be good for those <br>
kids over there in Baghdad,&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
But Betty Coleman, 60, a speech pathologist at the University of Toledo who <br>
once taught at the University of Tennessee, said the nuclear warhead parts <br>
made at Y-12 were just as threatening.<br>
<br>
&quot;The climate right now is intense,&quot; said Coleman, her face stamped with a <br>
&quot;Stop the Bombs&quot; washable tattoo. &quot;I think many of us in this country, maybe <br>
a majority, are fearful.<br>
<br>
&quot;And I think that adding to the fear is the fact that we need to protect <br>
ourselves with weapons of mass destruction, that the way to protect <br>
ourselves is to destroy others.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Y-12 plant provided the highly enriched uranium for the first bomb <br>
dropped on Hiroshima on Aug. 6, 1945, and continues to refurbish parts for <br>
every warhead in the U.S. arsenal.<br>
<br>
Peace activists and the media were granted access to the Department of <br>
Energy facility in 1993 to see Y-12's highly enriched uranium vaults, but <br>
that's not likely to happen again with the war raging in Iraq.<br>
<br>
&quot;We respect their right to protest, but we will take steps to protect the <br>
plant,&quot; DOE-Oak Ridge spokesman Steven Wyatt said.<br>
<br>
For 15 years, peace activists have staged protests at Y-12 at least twice a <br>
year - once in April and the other on the Hiroshima anniversary.<br>
<br>
Nonviolent arrests are common. Fourteen people were arrested in a protest <br>
last August that drew about 550 demonstrators to the plant.<br>
<br>
Organizers said the cold weather and growing number of peace demonstrations <br>
may have kept the numbers down Sunday from previous predictions that up to <br>
600 might attend.<br>
<br>
Still, participants were encouraged.<br>
<br>
&quot;I think it is another good show of dissent against the current regime in <br>
the United States,&quot; said John Johnson, an organizer with the Earth First <br>
environmental group in Chattanooga. &quot;I am particularly happy that despite <br>
all the right-wing bashing and questioning of our patriotism that folks <br>
still take the First Amendment seriously and choose to express their love of <br>
this country.&quot;<br>
<br>
At one point in the 4 1/2-hour demonstration, when the peace activists had <br>
reached the Y-12 entrance and counterdemonstrators were shouting at them, <br>
members of both groups began singing &quot;The Star-Spangled Banner.&quot;<br>
